    <title>Bluetooth 6.0 has more security and precision for tracking and finding</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="An AirTag and the Find My app" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/alZCgb1-RJZM5AdjER2gFSI9ODE=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73565564/vpavic_4547_20210421_0097.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Photo by Vjeran Pavic / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="d1K5uG"&gt;The next generation of Bluetooth could make it easier to track down lost tech. On Tuesday, the Bluetooth Special Interest Group (SIG) &lt;a href="https://www.bluetooth.com/blog/now-available-new-version-of-the-bluetooth-core-specification/"&gt;announced the release of Bluetooth 6.0&lt;/a&gt;, which includes a new precision tracking feature that could improve the Find My networks from companies like Apple, Google, and Tile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="bQdvRn"&gt;Bluetooth is the protocol that controls wireless communication between devices. The Bluetooth SIG, which oversees the standard, periodically releases updates with new capabilities. &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2016/6/10/11900038/bluetooth-5-announced-double-range-4-times-speed"&gt;Bluetooth’s last major update&lt;/a&gt; took place in 2016.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="oWCQIh"&gt;Bluetooth 6.0 introduces a feature &lt;a href="https://www.bluetooth.com/learn-about-bluetooth/feature-enhancements/channel-sounding/"&gt;called Channel Sounding&lt;/a&gt;, which can determine the distance between two devices with “centimeter-level accuracy,” according to the Bluetooth SIG. To do this, it uses...&lt;/p&gt;
